'''''Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] young-adult novel series from authors [[Kevin J. Anderson]] and [[Rebecca Moesta]]. The series is set in [[23 ABY/Legends|23 ABY]] and follows the adventures of [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Solo twins (disambiguation)|twin]]s [[Darth Caedus|Jacen]] and [[Jaina Solo Fel|Jaina Solo]]. ''Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights'' comprises fourteen volumes that were published between [[1995]] and [[1998]] by [[Berkley Boulevard]]. A companion series titled ''[[Star Wars: Junior Jedi Knights]]'' was published concurrently.

The ''Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights'' novels were republished in several [[Science Fiction Book Club]] titles: [[Young Jedi Knights: The Rise of the Shadow Academy|''The Rise of the Shadow Academy'']] ([[1996]]), [[Young Jedi Knights: The Fall of the Diversity Alliance|''The Fall of the Diversity Alliance'']] (1998), [[Young Jedi Knights: Under Black Sun|''Under Black Sun'']] ([[1999]]), [[Young Jedi Knights: Jedi Shadow|''Jedi Shadow'']] ([[2002]]), and [[Young Jedi Knights: Jedi Sunrise|''Jedi Sunrise'']] ([[2003]]).

==Continuity==
''Young Jedi Knights'' was a very popular series of novels geared to teens and was instrumental in developing the characters of [[Darth Caedus|Jacen]] and [[Jaina Solo Fel|Jaina]]. Jaina truly takes after [[Han Solo/Legends|her father]], being more brash and mechanically inclined, while Jacen is more contemplative, attuned to nature, and has a corny sense of humor. The series would last fourteen books and introduce a supporting cast of young [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] characters – [[Tenel Ka Djo|Tenel Ka]], [[Lowbacca]], [[Zekk]], [[Raynar Thul]] – who would play important roles later in the timeline, starting with the [[Star Wars: The New Jedi Order|''New Jedi order'']] novels.<ref name="TERC" /> 

[[Qorl]]'s [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] designation of CE3K-1977 is a nod to [[Steven Spielberg]]'s [[Wikipedia: Close Encounters of the Third Kind|''Close Encounters of the Third Kind'']], a [[1977]] motion picture contemporary to ''[[Star Wars]]''. In a [[2002]] installment of [[The Official Star Wars Fact File]], a weekly periodical published by [[De Agostini]], Qoorl's character was combined with a stranded [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE fighter]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] first depicted in ''[[The Day after the Death Star!]]'', a comic strip published in ''[[Star Wars Weekly]]'' [[Star Wars Weekly 97|#97]]-[[Star Wars Weekly 99|99]] ([[1980]]) by [[Star Wars (Marvel UK)|Marvel's UK]] office.<ref name="TERC" />

